Workshop - Temporal and Spatial Autocorrelation

Xanthe Walker

2025-08-05

Introduction

In this workshop, we will explore how to detect and model temporal and spatial autocorrelation in ecological data.

We will use three examples:

  • Simple Temporal example: Abundance of moorhens on Kauai (Subset Hawaii dataset)
  • Multiple Temporal example: Abundance of different bird species on Kauai (Full Hawaii dataset)
  • Spatial example: Boreality index from boreal forest vegetation plots in Russia (Boreality dataset)

For each example, we will:

  1. Fit a model without autocorrelation
  2. Check for autocorrelation
  3. Fit and compare models with different correlation structures
  4. Select the best correlation structure using AIC
  5. Apply the selected correlation structure and continue with fixed effect selection

Part 1: Temporal Autocorrelation

Load Hawaii dataset

Hawaii <- read.csv("../../Data files/Hawaii.csv")
Hawaii$Birds <- sqrt(as.numeric(Hawaii$Moorhen.Kauai)) # transform abundance and only look at onbe species
head(Hawaii)
##   Year Stilt.Oahu Stilt.Maui Coot.Oahu Coot.Maui Moorhen.Kauai Rainfall
## 1 1956        163        169       528       177             2    15.16
## 2 1957        272        190       338       273            NA    15.48
## 3 1958        549        159       449       256             2    16.26
## 4 1959        533        211       822       170            10    21.25
## 5 1960         NA        232        NA       188             4    10.94
## 6 1961        134        155       717       149            10    19.93
##      Birds
## 1 1.414214
## 2       NA
## 3 1.414214
## 4 3.162278
## 5 2.000000
## 6 3.162278
# Remove missing data
Hawaii <- Hawaii %>%
  filter(!is.na(Birds), !is.na(Rainfall), !is.na(Year))

Step 1: Plot the data

ggplot(Hawaii, aes(x = Year, y = Birds, color = Rainfall)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "orange", high = "blue") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Moorhen abundance on Kauai")

Step 2: Fit a GLS model without correlation structure

We use gls() instead of lm() so we can later add correlation structures and compare models with the same fitting method (MLE).

birds_gls <- gls(Birds ~ Rainfall + Year,
                 data = Hawaii,
                 na.action = na.omit,
                 method = "ML")
tab_model(birds_gls, show.aic = TRUE, show.se = TRUE)
Birds
Predictors Estimates std. Error CI p
(Intercept) -477.66 56.42 -591.52-363.81 <0.001
Rainfall 0.00 0.05 -0.100.10 0.986
Year 0.25 0.03 0.190.30 <0.001
Observations 45
R2 0.638
AIC 218.886

Step 3: Check residuals for autocorrelation

First, plot residuals vs.time.

Hawaii$resid <- residuals(birds_gls, type = "normalized")
ggplot(Hawaii, aes(x = Year, y = resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Residuals vs Year")

The plot of residuals vs.year shows a clear pattern large positive residuals cluster in the 1990s, while negative residuals appear in the 1970s and early 2000s.
This violates the assumption of independence because residuals close in time appear more similar.

Then, use the autocorrelation function (ACF) and partial autocorrelation function (PACF).

acf(residuals(birds_gls, type = "normalized"))

pacf(residuals(birds_gls, type = "normalized"))

The ACF plot shows very high correlation at lag 1 (year-to-year), with gradual decay over several lags a hallmark of an autoregressive (AR) process.
The PACF plot drops sharply after lag 1, confirming that an AR(1) structure is a good starting choice for modeling the temporal correlation.

Together, these diagnostics tell us: - Observations are not independent in time. - We should test correlation structures such as AR(1), CAR(1), or ARMA to address this.

Step 4: Fit models with different temporal correlation structures

Compound symmetry (constant correlation)

birds_cs <- update(birds_gls,
                   correlation = corCompSymm(form = ~ Year))

AR(1) structure

birds_ar1 <- update(birds_gls,
                    correlation = corAR1(form = ~ Year))

Continuous-time AR(1)

birds_car1 <- update(birds_gls,
                     correlation = corCAR1(form = ~ Year))

ARMA(2,0) structure

birds_arma20 <- update(birds_gls,
                       correlation = corARMA(form = ~ Year, p = 2, q = 0))

Step 5: Compare temporal correlation structures

AIC(birds_gls, birds_cs, birds_ar1, birds_car1, birds_arma20)
##              df      AIC
## birds_gls     4 218.8858
## birds_cs      5 194.8577
## birds_ar1     5 192.0444
## birds_car1    5 192.0444
## birds_arma20  6 187.9519

Choose the lowest AIC as the best-supported correlation structure.

Step 6: Check residuals of best model

acf(residuals(birds_arma20, type = "normalized"))

pacf(residuals(birds_arma20 , type = "normalized"))

Part 2: Modeling with many time series

Load and reshape Hawaii dataset

Hawaii1 <- read.csv("../../Data files/Hawaii.csv")
head(Hawaii1)

## 4 1959        533        211       822       170            10    21.25
## 5 1960         NA        232        NA       188             4    10.94
## 6 1961        134        155       717       149            10    19.93
#reshape the data into long format
library(tidyr)
Hawaii_long <- Hawaii1 %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = Stilt.Oahu:Moorhen.Kauai,   # all bird columns
    names_to = "Species",              # new column for species/location
    values_to = "Count"                # new column for counts
  )

head(Hawaii_long)
## # A tibble: 6  4
##    Year Rainfall Species       Count
##   <int>    <dbl> <chr>         <int>
## 1  1956     15.2 Stilt.Oahu      163
## 2  1956     15.2 Stilt.Maui      169

## 5  1956     15.2 Moorhen.Kauai     2
## 6  1957     15.5 Stilt.Oahu      272
Hawaii_long=na.omit(Hawaii_long)

Step 1: Plot the data

ggplot(Hawaii_long, aes(x = Year, y = Count, color = Rainfall)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~Species)+
  scale_color_gradient(low = "orange", high = "blue") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Bird abundance on Kauai")

The faceted time series show that each bird species on Kauai has a unique abundance trajectory and level of variability.
Some species have large fluctuations over time, others are more stable.
The rainfall gradient (color) suggests that environmental variation may influence different species differently.

We also see that variance appears to differ between species this is heteroscedasticity.
A single variance assumption would not be appropriate, so well later model species-specific variances.

birds_gls <- gls(Count ~ Rainfall*Species + Year,

With species-specific variance:

birds_var <- varIdent(form = ~ 1 | Species)
all_var <- gls(Count ~ Rainfall*Species + Year,

AIC 2876.545

The first GLS model (birds_gls) assumes equal variance across all species.
The second model (all_var) uses varIdent to estimate separate residual variances for each species.

If the AIC is lower for all_var, that supports including species-specific variances.
This helps prevent species with naturally higher variation from having undue influence on the fit.

Step 3: Check residuals for autocorrelation

First, plot residuals vs.time.

Hawaii_long$resid <- residuals(all_var, type = "normalized")
ggplot(Hawaii_long, aes(x = Year, y = resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Residuals vs Year")

The residuals still show patterns over time, with clusters of positive or negative residuals.
This suggests temporal autocorrelation remains after accounting for heterogeneity in variance.

Then, use the autocorrelation function (ACF) and partial autocorrelation function (PACF).

acf(residuals(all_var, type = "normalized"))

pacf(residuals(all_var, type = "normalized"))

The ACF plot shows that, after accounting for heterogeneity between species, most autocorrelation has been removed correlations at all lags are close to zero and within the 95% confidence bounds (blue dashed lines).

The PACF plot confirms this: there is no strong pattern of partial autocorrelation, suggesting that the residuals are now largely independent.

This means that a temporal correlation structure (e.g., AR(1)) may still be worth testing, but it is unlikely to provide a large improvement compared to our heterogeneity-only model.

Step 4: Fit models with different temporal correlation structures

Compound symmetry (constant correlation)

birds_cs <- update(all_var,
                   correlation = corCompSymm(form = ~ Year|Species))

AR(1) structure

birds_ar1 <- update(all_var,
                    correlation = corAR1(form = ~ Year|Species))

Continuous-time AR(1)

birds_car1 <- update(all_var,
                     correlation = corCAR1(form = ~ Year|Species))

ARMA(2,0) structure

birds_arma20 <- update(all_var,
                       correlation = corARMA(form = ~ Year|Species, p = 2, q = 0))

Step 5: Compare temporal correlation structures

AIC(all_var, birds_cs, birds_ar1, birds_car1, birds_arma20)
##              df      AIC
## all_var      16 2823.137
## birds_cs     17 2825.137
## birds_ar1    17 2752.718
## birds_car1   17 2752.718
## birds_arma20 18 2754.630

Both the AR(1) and continuous AR(1) structures improve the AIC dramatically (~70 points lower) compared to the model with no temporal correlation, indicating that residual autocorrelation is present and these models account for it well.

The ARMA(2,0) also improves AIC substantially but does not outperform AR(1).
Compound symmetry increases AIC, so it is not supported.

Because AR(1) and continuous AR(1) give identical AIC here, we would choose AR(1) for simplicity and interpretability.

Step 6: Check residuals of best model

acf(residuals(birds_ar1, type = "normalized"))

pacf(residuals(birds_ar1 , type = "normalized"))

Step 7: Plot the final model

Hawaii_long$fit <- predict(birds_ar1)

allSites <- ggplot(Hawaii_long,
       mapping=aes(x=Year, y=Count)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_bw(base_size=14) + 
  facet_wrap(~Species) +
  ylab("Birds")

allSites +
  geom_line(data=Hawaii_long, 
            mapping=aes(y=fit), 
            color="deeppink")

The pink lines show the models predicted values for each species over time. While the model captures the overall trends well, it smooths out some of the high interannual variability seen in the observed data (black lines), which is expected given the AR(1) correlation structure and inclusion of species-specific variance terms.

Part 3: Spatial Autocorrelation

Load Boreality dataset

This dataset comes from a boreal forest in Tatarstan, Russia.

Response variable (Bor): Boreality index calculated as the number of species belonging to a set of boreal species divided by the total number of species at a site.

Predictor variable (Wet): Wetness index a measure of how wet or dry a site is.

Boreality <- read.csv("../../Data files/Boreality.csv")
Boreality$Bor <- sqrt(1000 * (Boreality$nBor + 1) / (Boreality$nTot))
Boreality <- na.omit(Boreality)

Step 1: Plot the data

ggplot(Boreality, aes(x = Wet, y = Bor)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(
    title = "Spatial distribution of Boreality index",
    x = "Wetness Index",
    y = "Boreal Index"
  )

The scatterplot above shows a clear positive relationship: wetter sites tend to have higher boreality values. However, before we trust this relationship and move on with inference, we must check whether residuals from our model are spatially autocorrelated because ignoring spatial correlation can bias standard errors and pvalues.

Step 2: Fit a GLS model without spatial correlation

We first fit a generalized least squares (GLS) model without any spatial correlation structure. This acts as our baseline model for comparison.

bor_gls <- gls(Bor ~ Wet, data = Boreality, method = "ML")
tab_model(bor_gls, show.aic = TRUE, show.se = TRUE)
Bor
Predictors Estimates std. Error CI p
(Intercept) 18.49 0.38 17.7419.23 <0.001
Wet 165.80 10.60 144.98186.62 <0.001
Observations 533
R2 0.315
AIC 2849.156

Step 3: Check residuals spatially

Bubble plot

We can visualize the residuals on the spatial coordinate system to see whether nearby sites have similar residual values.

Boreality$resid <- residuals(bor_gls, type = "normalized")
ggplot(Boreality, aes(x = x, y = y, color = resid, size = abs(resid))) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_gradient2() +
  theme_bw()

Interpretation:

  • Red dots indicate negative residuals; blue dots indicate positive residuals.

  • Dot size is proportional to the magnitude of the residuals (larger = greater deviation from the model prediction).

  • Ideally, we should see no obvious spatial pattern residuals should be randomly distributed across the study area.

  • In this case, there appears to be some spatial clustering: many positive residuals occur close together, and the same is true for negative residuals.

  • This suggests there may be spatial autocorrelation or a missing spatially structured predictor in the model.

Variogram

We can also use a variogram to check for spatial autocorrelation. The variogram measures the variability between pairs of observations at different distances.

If two sites are close to each other, and their residuals are similar, the semi-variance will be low suggests spatial dependence.

If residuals are very different, the semi-variance will be high suggests spatial independence.

The x-axis of the variogram plot shows the distance between site pairs, and the y-axis shows the semi-variance.

Key terms:

  • Range: the distance at which spatial dependence disappears (variogram levels off).

  • Sill: the semi-variance value at the range.

  • Nugget: the semi-variance at zero distance, representing measurement error or variation at very small scales.

The nlme package includes a built-in Variogram() function to plot these.

vario_bor <- Variogram(bor_gls, form = ~ x + y, resType = "normalized")
plot(vario_bor)

Interpretation:

  • Small semi-variance values indicate that residuals for nearby sites are more similar.

  • Larger values indicate that residuals are less similar.

  • In this case, the variogram shows a clear upward trend before leveling off, indicating spatial dependence up to ~1000 m.

  • What we want after accounting for spatial structure in the model is a flat variogram, meaning residuals are spatially independent

Step 4: Fit models with different spatial correlation structures

Exponential

bor_exp <- update(bor_gls,
                  correlation = corExp(form = ~ x + y, nugget = TRUE))

Gaussian

bor_gaus <- update(bor_gls,
                   correlation = corGaus(form = ~ x + y, nugget = TRUE))

Linear

#bor_lin <- update(bor_gls,
           #       correlation = corLin(form = ~ x + y, nugget = TRUE))

Ratio

bor_ratio <- update(bor_gls,
                    correlation = corRatio(form = ~ x + y, nugget = TRUE))

Spherical

bor_spher <- update(bor_gls,
                    correlation = corSpher(form = ~ x + y, nugget = TRUE))

Step 5: Compare spatial correlation structures

AIC(bor_gls, bor_exp, bor_gaus, bor_ratio, bor_spher)
##           df      AIC
## bor_gls    3 2849.156
## bor_exp    5 2740.233
## bor_gaus   5 2743.595
## bor_ratio  5 2740.979
## bor_spher  5 2740.056

Select the lowest AIC model.

Step 6: Check residuals of best spatial model

Exponential is generally easier to excplain:

vario_best <- Variogram(bor_exp, form = ~ x + y, resType = "normalized")
plot(vario_best)

A flat variogram after modeling indicates spatial independence.

Exercises

Exercise #1: Irish forest data

The data used are a subset of the data analysed in Cruikshanks et al.(2006), a technical report by the Environmental Protection Agency, Wexford, Ireland.
We only use the 2003 data, and several recordings were dropped.
The original research sampled 257 rivers in Ireland during 2002 and 2003.
One aim was to find a different tool for identifying acid-sensitive waters, which currently uses measures of pH.
The Sodium Dominance Index (SDI) was proposed as an alternative.
The motivation for this research is the increase in plantation forestry cover in Irish landscapes and its potential impacts on aquatic resources.

Tasks:

  1. Read the data from Irishforest.csv and inspect the first few lines to ensure it was read correctly.
  2. Pay careful attention to the following variables (pH is the response variable):
    • Sodium Dominance Index (SDI)
    • Status as forested or not
    • Altitude
  3. Plot the data of pH and forested status in sampling space (Easting and Northing). Does there appear to be spatial correlation?
  4. Fit a linear model with pH as a function of SDI, forested status, altitude, all two-way interactions, and the three-way interaction.
  5. Examine model assumptions using residual plots.
  6. Extract and plot the residuals spatially (colored by residual value). Are the residuals spatially correlated?
  7. Plot a variogram to assess spatial correlation.
  8. Add at least two different spatial correlation structures to the model.
  9. Compare models with different spatial correlation structures using AIC. Make a table of AIC values.
  10. Plot a variogram of the best model. Is the spatial correlation accounted for?
  11. If not, describe your next steps.

Exercise #2: Plankton / Cod dataset

Data from:
Freitas, C., E. M. Olsen, H. Knutsen, J. Albretsen, and E. Moland. 2016.
Temperature-associated habitat selection in a cold-water marine fish. Journal of Animal Ecology 85:628637.

The authors examined the effect of ocean temperature on dive depth of individually tagged Atlantic cod along the Norwegian coast.

Tasks:

  1. Read the data from Cod_Daily_Depth.csv and inspect the first few lines to ensure it was read correctly.
  2. Examine the structure of the dataset.
  3. Change the date column from day/month/year to year-month-day format using the lubridate package.
  4. Plot log-transformed dive depth as a function of temperature for each fish. Why log-transform depth here?
  5. Center the temperature predictor to reduce correlation between intercepts and slopes.
  6. Fit a mixed-effects model predicting dive depth from centered surface temperature with:
    • Random intercept for fish
    • Random slope for temperature_centered grouped by fish
    • Use nlme::lme (not lme4) so that we can model residual correlation.
  7. Examine the model fit. Plot fitted relationships for each fish.
  8. Plot residuals versus fitted values for each fish.
  9. Plot residuals versus date for each fish.
  10. Use the autocorrelation function (ACF) to examine correlation of residuals between days. How correlated are values one day apart?
  11. Add a temporal autocorrelation structure (corAR1()).
  12. Examine the residuals versus fitted values and versus date again, using type = "normalized" residuals.
  13. Plot the final fitted model.
    • Transform predictions from log(depth) back to depth for interpretation.
    • Use ggpredict for population-level predictions.
    • (Bonus) Plot a separate slope and intercept for each fish.

Note: The corAR1() correlation structure is just one of a number of temporal correlation structures we could have fit. It is the simplest, and probably most common to use. nmle allows us to also fit higher order auto regressive models in the residuals. For example, an AR2 model would also estimate a regression parameter for residuals that are 2 time steps apart. This, and possible moving average coefficients, can be estimated with the nlme::corARMA().

Models with different correlation structures can be compared via AIC, and perhaps more importantly, by inspecting the residuals yourself with well-thought-out plots. Zuur et al.makes the point that fitting any temporal autocorrelation structure is usually far more important than getting the perfect structure. Start with AR1 and try more complicated structures if that seems insufficient.
